<div id="ventilation-heating-lighting-etc-27586" class="section section-scrollmation scrollmation-two-column section-two-column-27586 viewport-height-minheight" data-possible-scrollmation data-scrollmation-container="#ventilation-heating-lighting-etc-27586">
  <div class="two-column-grid">
    <div class="column column-left main-column scrollmation-text">
      
        <div class="block text-block"><p><strong>VENTILATION AND HEATING</strong>  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/ventilation-heating-diagram_bw_large-lr_dk0plqz.jpg" data-src755="./media/ventilation-heating-diagram_bw_large-mr_8jlqfbn.jpg" data-src0="./media/ventilation-heating-diagram_bw_large-lr_dk0plqz.jpg" alt="Diagram indicating elements of the building&#x27;s natural heating and ventilation systems " title="Diagram indicating elements of the building&#x27;s natural heating and ventilation systems " />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Diagram indicating elements of the building's natural heating and ventilation systems </p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>We have ‘mixed-mode’ ventilation in the Living Planet Centre. That basically means we can open the windows when necessary but we can also control the airflow and temperature electronically - although without using conventional, energy-heavy air conditioning.  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/lpc-window-ventilation-opening_comp-lr_ug7nfx6.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-window-ventilation-opening_comp-mr_w80ow3c.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-window-ventilation-opening_comp-lr_ug7nfx6.jpg" alt="Windows can be opened to let in cool, fresh air when wanted" title="Windows can be opened to let in cool, fresh air when wanted" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Windows can be opened to let in cool, fresh air when wanted</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Natural ventilation is a cost-efficient way to improve indoor air quality and to reduce our carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions (to help address global warming and climate change). So it’s a crucial aspect of the Living Planet Centre design.  </p>
<p>A mini ‘traffic light’ system of green and red LED lights next to the windows shows us whether they should be opened for natural ventilation or kept closed to let the ‘building management system’ regulate the heating and cooling.  </p>
<p>The Living Planet Centre is also fitted with internal CO2 sensors for health reasons – if CO2 concentrations increase inside the building, fresh air flow is increased.  </p>
<p>Instead of the usual kind of air-conditioning we use a combination of earth ducts, wind cowls and ground source heat pumps to regulate the temperature all around the building – including to cool the electrical and IT equipment in the Data Centre.  </p>
<p>EARTH DUCTS<br />
Also called ‘earth tubes’, we have six of these large-diameter pipes (they’re almost big enough to walk through), with a combined length of 400m, buried about a metre under the building.  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/earth-duct-during-construction_comp-lr_4rih7nr.jpg" data-src755="./media/earth-duct-during-construction_comp-mr_zcwvqsa.jpg" data-src0="./media/earth-duct-during-construction_comp-lr_4rih7nr.jpg" alt="Part of the concrete earth duct tubing being lowered into position onsite" title="Part of the concrete earth duct tubing being lowered into position onsite" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Part of the concrete earth duct tubing being lowered into position onsite</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Air is drawn into these pipes at the surface and circulated underground. Because the ambient temperature below ground is a fairly constant 12°C, it means colder air entering these underground ducts will be warmed up to 12°C, whereas warmer air will be cooled to that level.  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-image">
  <div class="inline-media">
    


    <div class="inline-image">
      
      <img src="./media/lpc-earth-ducts-top-closeup2_comp_siyregl-lr.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-earth-ducts-top-closeup2_comp_siyregl-mr.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-earth-ducts-top-closeup2_comp_siyregl-lr.jpg" alt="Above-ground top section of earth ducts, which draw in air to be cooled or heated underground" title="Above-ground top section of earth ducts, which draw in air to be cooled or heated underground" />
      
    </div>
    
      <p class="media-block-caption caption">
        Above-ground top section of earth ducts, which draw in air to be cooled or heated underground
      </p>
    
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block text-block"><p>This air is then fed into our air-handling units for further heating or cooling as needed (assisted by our <a href="http://www.wwf.org.uk/livingplanetcentrestory/#technology-67316" target="_blank">ground source heat pumps</a>, more about which later) and then distributed around the building.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/lpc-mero-flooring-w-vents_comp-lr_sy1tchl.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-mero-flooring-w-vents_comp-mr_vjduuvk.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-mero-flooring-w-vents_comp-lr_sy1tchl.jpg" alt="Floor vents are used to enhance air flow around the building" title="Floor vents are used to enhance air flow around the building" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Floor vents are used to enhance air flow around the building</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block media-block media-block-video">
  <div class="inline-media">
    

    <div class="inline-video" data-video-player>
      <video class="video-js vjs-default-skin" width="100%" height="100%" preload="none" controls poster="./media/energy-heating-building-vid_comp.jpg" alt="" aria-label="" ref="video" data-setup='{"controls":true,"autoplay":false,"preload":"none","width":"100%","height":"100%"}'>

          <source src="./media/lpc_building_energyvideo_comp_2u20e4z.mp4" type="video/mp4"/><source src="./media/video_file_iijlhzh.webm" type="video/webm"/>
          <img src="./media/energy-heating-building-vid_comp.jpg" title="Your browser does not support the <video> tag" alt="video fallback image"/>
      </video>
    </div>
    


  </div>
</div>
<div class="block text-block"><p><a href="http://www.wwf.org.uk/livingplanetcentrestory/#technology-67316" target="_blank">&gt; Find out more about our ground source heat pumps in the <strong>Technology</strong> section.</a>  </p>
<p>WIND COWLS  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-image">
  <div class="inline-media">
    


    <div class="inline-image">
      
      <img src="./media/lpc-wind-cowl-closeup_comp-lr_yhqcp5s.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-wind-cowl-closeup_comp-mr_kyaprb6.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-wind-cowl-closeup_comp-lr_yhqcp5s.jpg" alt="" title="" />
      
    </div>
    

  </div>
</div>
<div class="block text-block"><p>The four, 4m-high funnel-like cowls on the roof are another low-energy way to improve airflow in the building. Basically they’re wind-driven ventilators that can be opened and closed when needed.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/wind-cowl-and-louvres_comp-lr_y9czxgq.jpg" data-src755="./media/wind-cowl-and-louvres_comp-mr_hyydqaw.jpg" data-src0="./media/wind-cowl-and-louvres_comp-lr_y9czxgq.jpg" alt="One of our four wind cowls on the roof" title="One of our four wind cowls on the roof" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>One of our four wind cowls on the roof</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Each cowl rotates on specially designed bearings, aligning itself so its back faces into the wind. As the wind blows over the cowl, low pressure created inside it produces a vacuum, sucking out the warm, stale air from inside the building.  </p>
<p>Air also circulates through a specially designed gap (a ‘plenum’) in the flooring system. The floor panels themselves are carefully sealed to be airtight, to avoid unwanted air leaks or draughts.   </p>
<p>Sitting above an open-sided car park can raise design concerns over cold air leaking into the Living Planet Centre. The builders, and flooring installers in particular, had to be vigilant about ‘cold-bridging’ (or ‘thermal bridging’) – avoiding potential weakspots in a building’s insulation, often at a junction between floors, walls, roofs or windows, where heat can escape or draughts come in.  </p>
<p><strong>LIGHTING</strong>  </p>
<p>Natural daylight was always central to the design and layout of the Living Planet Centre – not only to cut down on electricity use but for health and wellbeing reasons too.  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/natural-lighting-and-striplights_comp-lr_rbanvuy.jpg" data-src755="./media/natural-lighting-and-striplights_comp-mr_yyrtrp6.jpg" data-src0="./media/natural-lighting-and-striplights_comp-lr_rbanvuy.jpg" alt="Natural light is at the heart of our building&#x27;s design" title="Natural light is at the heart of our building&#x27;s design" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Natural light is at the heart of our building's design</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Our careful design and planning stages took into consideration factors like seasonal variations – in both heating and lighting – as the sun’s position changes in relation to the building.   </p>
<p>The large amount of glass (we have more than 100 glazed units), especially in the roof, means the inside of the building gets twice as much natural light as the average office.  </p>
<p>In case the sunlight gets too glaring, we have a combination of fixed and automated shading panels of all shapes and sizes.   </p>
<p>An intelligent control system (designed by Levolux) takes into account the position of the sun and daylight levels at any given time and automatically adjusts the position of the fabric roller blinds to partially or completely shade windows and rooflights.  </p>
<p>Our daylighting target for people’s desks was 300 lux (1 ‘lux’ is equivalent to the light of one candle per square metre). Low-energy desk lamps can increase that to 500 lux.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/lpc-interior-lighting_comp-lr_ej0ajaw.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-interior-lighting_comp-mr_oo2r5jd.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-interior-lighting_comp-lr_ej0ajaw.jpg" alt="The natural daylight can be augmented by low-energy strip or spot-lighting when required" title="The natural daylight can be augmented by low-energy strip or spot-lighting when required" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>The natural daylight can be augmented by low-energy strip or spot-lighting when required</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>On less bright days we can turn on general overhead office lighting – a mix of energy-efficient fluorescent and LED lamps.   </p>
<p>Our total electrical lighting load is only 5.5 watts per square metre, considerably below the average for office space – but clever design makes it seem much brighter.  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/lpc-desk-lights_comp-lr_gwebsdo.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-desk-lights_comp-mr_ejuqmlm.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-desk-lights_comp-lr_gwebsdo.jpg" alt="Working positions have low-energy anglepoise desk lamps" title="Working positions have low-energy anglepoise desk lamps" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Working positions have low-energy anglepoise desk lamps</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>Light sensors inside and outside the building detect when natural light levels fall and rise, and adjust the electric lighting appropriately.  </p>
<p>Occupancy (movement) sensors in meeting rooms and toilets, and a ‘last-out’ function, help to make sure no unnecessary lights are left on.   </p>
<p>Movement sensors mean that the lights can sometimes go out in certain areas if everyone stays still for too long, but the system has a manual override. Besides, it’s a useful reminder that it’s not healthy to be sitting still in one place for too long!  </p>
<p><strong>SOUND / ACOUSTICS</strong>  </p>
<p>The Living Planet Centre design and planning process included careful consideration of the acoustics and sonic effects of the building.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/mezzanine-lighting-with-shutters-closed_comp-lr_tnc686z.jpg" data-src755="./media/mezzanine-lighting-with-shutters-closed_comp-mr_7cexleq.jpg" data-src0="./media/mezzanine-lighting-with-shutters-closed_comp-lr_tnc686z.jpg" alt="There&#x27;s acoustic damping fabric behind the slats in the ceiling panels" title="There&#x27;s acoustic damping fabric behind the slats in the ceiling panels" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>There's acoustic damping fabric behind the slats in the ceiling panels</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>It’s not just an issue of how noise (from outside and inside the building) would impact on the people working there, but also the environmental effects of noise on neighbours and local wildlife. We considered this right from the construction stage.  </p>
<p>Internally, a curved ceiling like the Living Planet Centre’s can cause acoustic problems in a building – with sound reflections becoming focused in certain areas, causing ‘loud spots’ and echoes.   </p>
<p>Acoustic specialists Cole Jarman helped come up with a clever solution that would make 30% of the ceiling (as well as more than half the wall areas) acoustically absorptive, by hiding special panels of mineral fibre behind the roof and wall panels.  </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-image">
  <div class="inline-media">
    


    <div class="inline-image">
      
      <img src="./media/lpc-construction_ceilingtiles-lr_dmidnhv.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-construction_ceilingtiles-mr_o6epfuh.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-construction_ceilingtiles-lr_dmidnhv.jpg" alt="Sound-absorbing fabric panels, exposed during ceiling construction" title="Sound-absorbing fabric panels, exposed during ceiling construction" />
      
    </div>
    
      <p class="media-block-caption caption">
        Sound-absorbing fabric panels, exposed during ceiling construction
      </p>
    
  </div>
</div>
<div class="block text-block"><p>We’ve also installed a sound-masking system which generates subtle ‘white noise’ at sound frequencies that mask background chatter and office noise – adding soothing hints of birdsong to enhance the feeling of calm.  </p>
<p>The flooring had to be specially designed to counteract vibrations from footsteps and avoid transmitting any unwanted sounds around the building.  </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/cisco-auditorium-with-acoustic-panels_comp-lr_g0uvfkf.jpg" data-src755="./media/cisco-auditorium-with-acoustic-panels_comp-mr_9yyqrhz.jpg" data-src0="./media/cisco-auditorium-with-acoustic-panels_comp-lr_g0uvfkf.jpg" alt="After testing with a 3D model, extra fabric-covered acoustic panels were added to the side walls of the auditorium to improve sound quality" title="After testing with a 3D model, extra fabric-covered acoustic panels were added to the side walls of the auditorium to improve sound quality" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>After testing with a 3D model, extra fabric-covered acoustic panels were added to the side walls of the auditorium to improve sound quality</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>After we moved in and tried out the various spaces, we added some more acoustic panels in the smaller meeting rooms, to make them better for teleconferencing, as well as reducing noise reverberations in the Learning Zone and boardroom.  </p>
<p><strong>WATER SYSTEMS</strong>  </p>
<p>To reduce the amount of fresh water we use from the mains supply for things like watering our plants and flushing our toilets, we harvest rainwater.   </p></div><div class="block media-block media-block-video">
  <div class="inline-media">
    

    <div class="inline-video" data-video-player>
      <video class="video-js vjs-default-skin" width="100%" height="100%" preload="none" controls poster="./media/wateraroundbuildingvideostill_comp.jpg" alt="" aria-label="" ref="video" data-setup='{"controls":true,"autoplay":false,"preload":"none","width":"100%","height":"100%"}'>

          <source src="./media/lpc_water_cycles_comp_wovuhho.mp4" type="video/mp4"/><source src="./media/video_file_ptgqpi4.webm" type="video/webm"/>
          <img src="./media/wateraroundbuildingvideostill_comp.jpg" title="Your browser does not support the <video> tag" alt="video fallback image"/>
      </video>
    </div>
    


  </div>
</div>
<div class="block text-block"><p>Rain falling on the roof, paved walkways, ramps and terrace is caught in gutters and gullies and diverted via attenuation tanks within the entrance level structure to a huge 35,000-litre holding tank underground.   </p>
<p>We also recycle ‘greywater’ from hand basins and showers inside the building, and pass it through a filter and UV treatment unit for disinfection, before it’s reused in the toilets.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/water-recycling-graphic_comp-lr_orkt7kq.jpg" data-src755="./media/water-recycling-graphic_comp-mr_wtpmz4x.jpg" data-src0="./media/water-recycling-graphic_comp-lr_orkt7kq.jpg" alt="Water recycling systems around the building" title="Water recycling systems around the building" />
    </div>
    
    <p class="scrollmation-image-block-caption caption">
      <p>Water recycling systems around the building</p>
    </p>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>If there’s not enough rain, mains water will be used. If there’s too much rain, the excess goes into the wetland area as part of our sustainable urban drainage system. Once that’s full, the water there will overflow into the nearby Basingstoke Canal.   </p></div><div class="block scrollmation-image-block scrollmation-image-block-">
  <div class="inline-media">
    <div class="inline-image">
      <img src="./media/lpc-gutter-w-rainwater-harvesting-stat_comp-lr_jfoshwr.jpg" data-src755="./media/lpc-gutter-w-rainwater-harvesting-stat_comp-mr_rbrmxgl.jpg" data-src0="./media/lpc-gutter-w-rainwater-harvesting-stat_comp-lr_jfoshwr.jpg" alt="" title="" />
    </div>
    
  </div>
</div><div class="block text-block"><p>The below-ground drainage system has been coordinated with the tree protection plan, and porous paving has been specified for surfacing the access paths and cycle racks area, to minimise the impact on tree roots.  </p>
<p>Sink taps in the building are fitted with ‘passive infrared’ motion sensors to save water. Showers have timer switches and the WC cisterns are dual-flush to reduce water use. We also use energy-efficient zip taps for instant hot water for drinks.  </p></div><aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="1.83526011561">
  

        <img alt="Diagram indicating elements of the building&amp;#39;s natural heating and ventilation systems " class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/ventilation-heating-diagram_bw_large-lr_dk0plqz.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/ventilation-heating-diagram_bw_large-mr_8jlqfbn.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Diagram indicating elements of the building's natural heating and ventilation systems </p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="1.48148148148">
  

        <img alt="Windows can be opened to let in cool, fresh air when wanted" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/lpc-window-ventilation-opening_comp-lr_ug7nfx6.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/lpc-window-ventilation-opening_comp-mr_w80ow3c.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Windows can be opened to let in cool, fresh air when wanted</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small portrait-image" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="0.77519379845">
  

        <img alt="Floor vents are used to enhance air flow around the building" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/lpc-mero-flooring-w-vents_comp-lr_sy1tchl.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/lpc-mero-flooring-w-vents_comp-mr_vjduuvk.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Floor vents are used to enhance air flow around the building</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="1.08499095841">
  

        <img alt="Part of the concrete earth duct tubing about to be installed underground on-site" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/earth-duct-during-construction_comp-lr_4rih7nr.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/earth-duct-during-construction_comp-mr_zcwvqsa.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Part of the concrete earth duct tubing about to be installed underground on-site</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small portrait-image" data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="0.688245315162">
  

        <img alt="One of our four wind cowls on the roof" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/wind-cowl-and-louvres_comp-lr_y9czxgq.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/wind-cowl-and-louvres_comp-mr_hyydqaw.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">One of our four wind cowls on the roof</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="2.03389830508">
  

        <img alt="Natural light is at the heart of our building&amp;#39;s design" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/natural-lighting-and-striplights_comp-lr_rbanvuy.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/natural-lighting-and-striplights_comp-mr_yyrtrp6.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Natural light is at the heart of our building's design</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="2.00668896321">
  

        <img alt="The natural daylight can be augmented by low-energy strip or spot-lighting when required" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/lpc-interior-lighting_comp-lr_ej0ajaw.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/lpc-interior-lighting_comp-mr_oo2r5jd.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">The natural daylight can be augmented by low-energy strip or spot-lighting when required</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="2.23048327138">
  

        <img alt="Working positions have low-energy anglepoise desk lamps" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/lpc-desk-lights_comp-lr_gwebsdo.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/lpc-desk-lights_comp-mr_ejuqmlm.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Working positions have low-energy anglepoise desk lamps</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="1.5037593985">
  

        <img alt="Mezzanine level (blinds closed, lights on). There&amp;#39;s acoustic damping fabric hidden behind those slats in the ceiling panels" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/mezzanine-lighting-with-shutters-closed_comp-lr_tnc686z.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/mezzanine-lighting-with-shutters-closed_comp-mr_7cexleq.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">Mezzanine level (blinds closed, lights on). There's acoustic damping fabric hidden behind those slats in the ceiling panels</p>
    
</aside>
<aside class="scrollmation-inline hide-small " data-resize-element=".scrollmation-two-column .secondary-column" data-copy-element data-scrollmation-slide  data-media-ratio="1.5037593985">
  

        <img alt="After testing with a 3D model, extra fabric-covered acoustic panels were added to the side walls of the auditorium to improve sound quality" class="inline-image edit-image-button" src="./media/cisco-auditorium-with-acoustic-panels_comp-lr_g0uvfkf.jpg" data-min-width-1401="./media/cisco-auditorium-with-acoustic-panels_comp-mr_9yyqrhz.jpg" />
      
      <p class="caption">After testing with a 3D model, extra fabric-covered acoustic panels were added to the side walls of the auditorium to improve sound quality</p>
    
